Exploring the BRFSS Data

Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System

Setup

Load packages

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(psych)
library(tidyr)

Load data

Make sure your data and R Markdown files are in the same directory. When loaded your data file will be called brfss2013. Delete this note when before you submit your work.

load("brfss2013.RData")

Part 1: Data

According to the dataset documentation, this BRFSS data was collected in 2 main ways:

1.Landline telephone surveys

  • When conducting the landline surveys, adults were randomly selected in a household.

2.Cellular telephone survers

  • When conducting the cell phone surverys, the subjects were adults who have cell phones and resides in either a private residence or college housing.

The subjects were from all 50 states and some US territories.

Quoting from the official CDC BRFSS Data Documentation

States may determine that they would like to sample by county, public health district or other sub-state geography in order to make comparisons of geographic areas with their states. In order to conduct the BRFSS, states obtain samples of telephone numbers from CDC. States then review their sampling methodology with a state statistician and CDC to make sure data collection procedures are in place to follow the methodology.

Additional key pieces of information regarding sampling methodology are as follows:

  • Overall: Geographic Stratification
  • Landline Survey: Telephone numbers (Further Stratified Sampling) & Respondent (Random Sample)
  • Cell Phone Survey: Cluster sampling (per states particular method) & random sampling

Thus, the sampling methodology for the survery allows for generalization of findings because of the random sampling. However, given this is an observational study (not an experiment), findings do not prove causality.

Part 2: Research questions

Research quesion 1:

Is there a relationship between sodium intake and physical/mental health? In my experience, most people that closely monitor their food consumption pay more attention to micro and macro nutrients than sodium intake. Personally, I watch what I eat closely, but without regard to how much sodium I consume. It would be interesting for me to see if the self-reported data on physical/mental health varies between subjects with different consumptions of sodium.

Research quesion 2:

How does sleep affect physical and mental health as you age? It is no secret that sleep is important and often overlooked by many people, but I would love to compare physical and mental health between different age group-sleep time combinations.

Research quesion 3:

Is there a correlation between alcohol consumption, tobacco use, and income? Alcohol consumption and tobacco use are often looked at as vices or guilty pleasures for many people. I am interested in exploring the usage of these activities among different groups of income categories to see if they can also serve as predictors of income.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

Research quesion 1: Is there a relationship between sodium intake and physical/mental health?

The wtchsalt variable has 2 main values (Yes/No) and many missing/refused/dont know. Its an optional module (states can decide whether or not to ask the questions), so it makes sense that many values are missing.

brfss2013 %>% group_by(wtchsalt) %>% summarise (count=n())
## Warning: Factor `wtchsalt` contains implicit NA, consider using
## `forcats::fct_explicit_na`
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##   wtchsalt  count
##   <fct>     <int>
## 1 Yes       74389
## 2 No        53638
## 3 <NA>     363748

Im only concerned about the non-NA values, so Ill filter them out. For convenience, Ill assign the dataset with NAs filtered out to a new DataFrame.

brfss_wslt_nona <- brfss2013 %>% filter(!is.na(wtchsalt))

Lets compare the Yes group and the No group by BMI (X_bmi5), reported weight (weight2), days physical health not good (physhlth), and number days mental health not good (menthlth). Lets take a look at their data types.

sapply(brfss_wslt_nona %>% select(X_bmi5,wtkg3,physhlth,menthlth),class)
##    X_bmi5     wtkg3  physhlth  menthlth 
## "integer" "integer" "integer" "integer"

Okay so these are all numeric data that can be summarized. Lets look at the max and min values for each of them to see if there are any obvious outliers.

sodium_analysis <- brfss_wslt_nona %>% select(X_bmi5,wtkg3,physhlth,menthlth,wtchsalt)

  • By looking at the max column of this table, it looks like BMI might have outliers. Its implied there are 2 decimal places, so the maximum value is 91.45. Over 30 is considered obese, so this may be an error. Well plot it later just to see what the distribution looks like.
  • Wtkg3 might have outliers as well. This should be in kilograms with 2 decimal places, and so shows that the maximum value in the wtkg3 is 272.16kg. This could very well be a valid value, though. Ill take a look at the plot just to see what the distribution looks like.
  • Physhlth and Menhlth seem okay. No obvious outliers there.
ggplot(sodium_analysis,aes(X_bmi5))+geom_histogram(bins=50)
## Warning: Removed 6027 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

ggplot(sodium_analysis,aes(wtkg3))+geom_histogram(bins=50)
## Warning: Removed 4630 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

Both distributions show some huge outliers, and I dont want these outliers to affect my comparison because Im going to aggregate these values between the Yes group and the No group, so Im going to filter out X_bmi5>5500 and wtkg3>16500.

sodium_analysis <- sodium_analysis %>% filter(X_bmi5<=5500,wtkg3 <= 16500)

Now Im going to group these by wtchsalt and aggregate by mean. Just for convenience, Im going to filter out NAs, however I realize this may not be a very valid approach to dealing with missing values.

# Filtering out NA's
sa_no_na <- sodium_analysis %>% group_by(wtchsalt) %>% filter(!is.na(X_bmi5),!is.na(physhlth),!is.na(menthlth))

# Using gather to create a long form of the data for plotting
sa_no_na_long <- tidyr::gather(sa_no_na,key=metric,value=values,-wtchsalt)

# Plotting using facet_wrap to see several box plots
ggplot(sa_no_na_long,aes(x=wtchsalt,y=values,group=wtchsalt))+
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=wtchsalt))+facet_wrap(metric ~ ., scales = "free_y")

Conclusion By looking at these boxplots, it doesnt seem like the population that responded Yes to wtchsalt differred very highly from the population that responded No to wtchsalt. The biggest differences I see are that the Yes group seemed to have more days in which they felt physically bad (physhlth) and had a higher calculated body mass index (X_bmi). This is contary to what I would have expected, but I suppose a confounding factor is that people that watch salt may choose to do so because they may be in slightly worse physical condition than those who do not watch their salt intake. In conclusion, I have no significant discoveries on whether salt affects physical or mental well being per the analysis above.

Research quesion 2: How does sleep affect physical and mental health as you age?

Lets start by looking at sleep time by age groups.

ggplot(brfss2013,aes(X_ageg5yr,sleptim1))+geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 7387 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

This didnt work out very well. X_ageg5yr is a categorical variable that contains approximately 5 year age groups. sleptim1 is a discrete variable that should be between 1-24, so it looks like there are outliers (100 and 450) that should be removed.

sleptim_ol_rem <- brfss2013 %>% filter(sleptim1<=24)
ggplot(sleptim_ol_rem,aes(x=X_ageg5yr,y=sleptim1))+
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(x="Age Groups",y="Sleep Time (Hours)")

This doesnt appear to show any differences between reported sleep time among the age groups. It may be too distributed. Lets try this with bigger age groups. Ill do this manually by dividing X_age80 (numerical variable ranging from 18-80) into 5 groups 1. 18-32 2. 33-44 3. 45-56 4. 57-68 5. 69-80

# Making cuts to create 5 age groups
b = c(18,32,44,56,68,80)
l = c("18-32","33-44","45-56","57-68","69-80")
sleptim_ol_rem$age_g_5 <- cut(sleptim_ol_rem$X_age80,breaks=b,labels=l)

# Replotting (And removed NAs for age since their age is unknown)
sleptim_ol_rem_age <- sleptim_ol_rem %>% filter(!is.na(age_g_5))
ggplot(sleptim_ol_rem_age,aes(x=age_g_5,y=sleptim1))+
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(x="Age Groups",y="Sleep Time (Hours)")

This is a bit easier to read. Still unhelpful since it doesnt show any apparent trends in sleep patterns between the age groups. So lets change our strategy and just create a categorical variable with 2 values: Inadequate sleep (<=6 hours) and Adequate sleep (>6 hours), then use that as a fill to compare phys health between age groups.

# Creating the categories
b <- c(0,6,24)
l <- c("Inadequate Sleep","Adequate Sleep")
sleptim_ol_rem_age$sleep_quality <- cut(sleptim_ol_rem_age$sleptim1,breaks=b,labels=l)

ggplot(sleptim_ol_rem_age,aes(x=age_g_5,y=physhlth,fill=sleep_quality))+
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(x="Age Groups",y="Days Feeling Physically Not Good")
## Warning: Removed 9872 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

Thats interesting! So I interpret this as the following

Older people tend to feel physically not good more often when they get inadequate sleep (<=6 hours).

Lets see this same analysis on mental health.

ggplot(sleptim_ol_rem_age,aes(x=age_g_5,y=menthlth,fill=sleep_quality))+
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(x="Age Groups",y="Days Feeling Mentally Not Good")
## Warning: Removed 7729 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

This is surprising! Im interpretting this as the following

Younger people tend to feel mentally not good more often when they get inadequate sleep (<=6 hours).

Conclusion This is the reverse of my intuition. After seeing the box plots on physical health, I thought that mental health would have a similar relationship with sleep and age, but the analysis above shows something a bit different. Older people tend to have more days feeling physically not good with inadequate sleep, but younger people arent as affected. Younger people have had more days feeling mentally not good with inadequate sleep, but older people dont seem to be affected.

Research quesion 3: Is there a correlation between alcohol consumption, tobacco use, and income?

Luckily, the dataset comes with some useful variables for this analysis.

Lets start with looking at income2 (ordinal variable - income levels) for income and avedrnk2 (discrete variable - Avg alcoholic drinks per day).

Lets remove NA values from income2 since these income levels arent reported.

inc_no_na <- brfss2013 %>% filter(!is.na(income2))
ggplot(inc_no_na,aes(income2,avedrnk2))+stat_summary(geom="bar",fun.y = "mean") + coord_flip()
## Warning: Removed 212571 rows containing non-finite values (stat_summary).

This was easy to plot. Note that we get a warning saying many non-finite values were removed. This is because there are over 250,000 missing values for avedrnk2. However, this can be interpreted as 0 drinks for our purposes (and this makes sense given non-missing values range between 1-76).

Now lets just add in a fill on X_smoker3. Variable details Categorical 1. Current & Everyday Smoker 2. Current & Some Days Smoker 3. Former Smoker 4. Never Smoked

ggplot(inc_no_na,aes(income2,avedrnk2,fill=X_smoker3))+stat_summary(geom="bar",fun.y = "mean") + coord_flip()
## Warning: Removed 212571 rows containing non-finite values (stat_summary).

Lots of NA values in X_smoker3. This is a computed value that uses other variables. Lets see if smokday2 provides a more helpful view.

ggplot(inc_no_na,aes(income2,avedrnk2,fill=smokday2))+stat_summary(geom="bar",fun.y = "mean") + coord_flip()
## Warning: Removed 212571 rows containing non-finite values (stat_summary).

This is a bit better.

Conclusion Per the bar plots above, Ive observed the following - Higher income groups tend to consume significantly less acohol per month than lower income groups. - Approximate ratio of reported current smokers to total population seems roughly consistent across income groups, showing no apparent relationship between income and tobacco use.

It is also worth calling out the non-responses or potential risk of inaccurate responses within these sin categories. As always with observational studies, these findings should be taken with a grain of salt.
